04426nam a22005775i 9780774835947DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748359477 a10.59962/97807748359472doi  a(DE-B1597)662070  a(OCoLC)1012845736  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRT82b.A767 2018 7aMED0390002bisacsh04a610.732231 aArmstrong-Reid, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChina Gadabouts :bNew Frontiers of Humanitarian Nursing, 1941–51 /cSusan Armstrong-Reid. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2017] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (356 p.) :b34 photos, 11 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tFrom Regional War to Global War, 1941–45 -- tIntroduction to Part 1 -- tTrial by Fire -- tA Marriage of Convenience -- tThe Salween Campaign -- t“China Needs Good Men, and Still Better Women” -- tBaoshan -- tNavigating New Humanitarian Frontiers, 1945–51 -- tIntroduction to Part 2 -- tThe Road to Henan -- tHenan -- t“Early Team” -- tUnwelcome Visitors: Negotiating Access with the Communists, 1947–51 -- tIntroduction to Part 3 -- tNursing beyond the Trenches, 1947–50 -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tAbbreviations Used in Notes -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Sino-Japanese War (1937–45) had a devastating impact on China’s civilian population. Braving bandits, disease, and dangerous roads, the China Convoy – a Quaker-sponsored humanitarian unit – delivered medical supplies and provided famine relief in the unoccupied territory of “Free China” and later to both sides in the ensuing civil war. China Gadabouts examines the contested roles played by Western and Chinese nurses in the Convoy’s humanitarian efforts from 1941 to 1951. In so doing, it re-examines the quandaries of Quakers’ purportedly apolitical global engagement that remain salient for contemporary humanitarians. Susan Armstrong-Reid explores how this work gave meaning to the women’s lives and how they attempted to carve out personal and professional space despite a chaotic, unfamiliar, and occasionally hostile environment. China Gadabouts illuminates the ethical dilemmas, professional challenges, and opportunities presented by humanitarian nursing within a Western-based relief organization, while acknowledging its contentious imperial role. In doing so, it spotlights an understudied area of global nursing – its role within INGOs, now more active than ever in global health care.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHumanitarian assistancexHistoryx20th centuryxChina. 0aNursingvCongresses. 0aNursingxHistoryx20th centuryxChina. 0aNursing. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311141792940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483594740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774835947423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774835947/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-141792-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles